import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler,StandardScaler
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#show the difference between the apartment types count (4 overall types)
df=pd.read_csv("NY Realstate Pricing.csv")
rooms_count=df['room_type'].value_counts().unique()
rooms_type=df['room_type'].unique()

apart_df = pd.DataFrame({'room type':rooms_type,'room count':rooms_count})
column_data = apart_df['room count']
categories = apart_df['room type']
colors = ['red', 'blue', 'yellow', 'lime']
plt.bar(categories, column_data,color=colors)

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Category')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Room Types')

# Display the chart
plt.show()

#dividing the apartments types to pie charts and finding the percentage of the prices (high,medium,low) for each apartment indivisually

num_categories = 3
df['Price Category'] = pd.qcut(df['price'], q=num_categories, labels=['low', 'medium', 'high'])
df['Price Category']

grouped_data = df.groupby('room_type')['Price Category'].value_counts()

# Get unique apartment types
apartment_types = df['room_type'].unique()

# Create a separate pie chart for each apartment type
for apartment_type in apartment_types:
    apartment_data = grouped_data[apartment_type]
    labels = apartment_data.index
    values = apartment_data.values
    
    # Create a new figure and axis for each pie chart
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    
    # Create the pie chart
    ax.pie(values, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%')
    ax.set_title(f'Pie Chart - Apartment Type: {apartment_type}')
    
    plt.show()


#dividing the prices to 3 categories and see the differnce between them in a graph
prices_count=df['Price Category'].value_counts().unique()
prices_type=df['Price Category'].unique()

apart_df = pd.DataFrame({'prices type':prices_type,'prices count':prices_count})
column_data = apart_df['prices count']
categories = apart_df['prices type']
colors = ['red', 'blue', 'yellow', 'lime']
plt.bar(categories, column_data,color=colors)

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Category')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Price Categories')

# Display the chart
plt.show()

#creating a heatmap to see the correlation between the days occupied and the apartment type in 2019

import seaborn as sns

# Filter the DataFrame for the specified apartment types


# Reshape the filtered data for heatmap
heatmap_data = df.pivot_table(index='room_type', aggfunc='mean', values='days_occupied_in_2019')

# Create a heatmap using seaborn
sns.heatmap(heatmap_data, cmap='YlOrRd', annot=True, fmt='g')

# Set the title and labels
plt.title('Days Occupied Heatmap')
plt.xlabel('Room Type')
plt.ylabel('Days Occupied')

# Show the heatmap
plt.show()

#this is a correlation matrix display with scatter graphs finding the correlation betweeen each two relevant columns
#obviously the correlation between the column and itself wont be scattered because its the same column
columns = ['days_occupied_in_2019', 'price', 'availability_2020',
           'minimum_nights', 'number_of_reviews', 'reviews_per_month']

# Create the scatter matrix plot
scatter_matrix = pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(df[columns], figsize=(15, 10))

# Customize the diagonal subplots
for i in range(len(columns)):
    scatter_matrix[i, i].set_xlabel(columns[i])
    scatter_matrix[i, i].set_ylabel(columns[i])

# Adjust spacing between subplots
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.3, hspace=0.3)

# Show the scatter matrix plot
plt.show()
